{
  "project": "fixture-shop",
  "title": "Webhook Signature Verification in verify.php",
  "slug": "webhook-signature-verification",
  "date": "2026-07-17",
  "depth": "intro",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "name": "HMAC Signature Verification",
      "definition": "A security technique where a sender and receiver share a secret key. The sender computes a hash-based message authentication code (HMAC) by running the message payload through a keyed hash function (such as SHA-256), then attaches the resulting signature to the request. The receiver independently recomputes the HMAC using the same key and compares it to the attached signature; a match proves the message was sent by someone who holds the secret and that the payload was not tampered with in transit."
    },
    {
      "name": "Constant-Time Comparison",
      "definition": "A method of comparing two strings or byte sequences that always takes the same amount of time regardless of how many leading bytes match. Standard string comparison short-circuits as soon as a mismatch is found, leaking timing information an attacker can exploit to guess a secret one byte at a time. Constant-time comparison eliminates this side channel by always iterating through all bytes before returning a result."
    }
  ],
  "files": ["src/verify.php"],
  "commit": "200eff3",
  "sources": [],
  "lesson": "The `verify()` function in `src/verify.php` decides whether an incoming webhook really came from the payment gateway. It recomputes an [[fixture-shop/_glossary#HMAC Signature Verification|HMAC-SHA256 signature]] over the raw request payload using the shared secret, then compares that against the signature header the sender provided. The comparison uses PHP's `hash_equals()`, a [[fixture-shop/_glossary#Constant-Time Comparison|constant-time comparison]], so an attacker cannot learn the correct signature byte by byte from response timing."
}

